---
description: "UI architecture doctrine (taxonomy, ownership, required structures)"
alwaysApply: true
---

## UI = Presentation Layer (MANDATORY)

UI exists to:
- display state
- forward player intent
- animate feedback

UI must NEVER:
- decide outcomes
- own game rules
- mutate authoritative state
- handle persistence or datastores

If gameplay cannot run without UI, UI is doing too much.

---

## UI Taxonomy (REQUIRED)

Every UI element MUST belong to exactly one type:

- TYPE 0 — HUD (passive, persistent)
- TYPE 1 — Button (atomic, stateless)
- TYPE 2 — Menu (stateful container)
- TYPE 3 — Interactive (state machine)

Do NOT mix types at the root level.
Types may be composed (e.g., Buttons inside Menus).

---

## Button Rule (TYPE 1 — MANDATORY)

- ImageButton = hitbox ONLY
- Visuals must be child ImageLabels/TextLabels
- Hitboxes must be tight and non-overlapping
- Button code may ONLY emit intent

Buttons must NEVER:
- run logic
- decide outcomes
- mutate state

---

## Menu Rule (TYPE 2 — REQUIRED STRUCTURE)

All Menus MUST follow this hierarchy exactly:

ScreenGui  
└─ MenuRoot  
   ├─ Dimmer  
   └─ Container  
      ├─ Header  
      ├─ Content  
      └─ Footer  

Locked names (use exactly):
MenuRoot, Dimmer, Container, Header, Content, Footer, CloseButton, Title

Rules:
- Only Content may scroll
- AspectRatioConstraint belongs ONLY on Container
- Menu owns open/close lifecycle ONLY

Menus must NEVER:
- run gameplay logic
- resolve purchases/equips
- touch persistence

---

## Interactive UI Rule (TYPE 3 — STATE MACHINE)

Interactive UI is:
- one root
- one lifecycle
- reused (never rebuilt per use)

Mounted ONLY under:
Container > Content > InteractiveUIRoot

Required state flow (never skip):
Idle → Armed → Active → Resolving → Cooldown → Idle

Interactive UI must NEVER:
- roll RNG
- decide outcomes
- mutate game state
